data.content:
## Migration Analysis

### Inventory of thread-termination APIs found

| API | Location | Pattern |
|-----|----------|---------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `Stop()` | Blocking call interruption — wakes thread from `WaitOne()` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Timeout enforcement — kills thread if `Join(5000)` fails |
| `while (true)` loop | `RunLoop()` | Cancellable work loop — no exit condition |

Both `Thread.Abort()` (throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`) and `Thread.Interrupt()` (`SYSLIB0046`) are unsupported/obsolete in modern .NET.

---

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new ManualResetEvent(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private readonly object _lock = new object();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var handles = new WaitHandle[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny returns index: 0 = new event, 1 = cancellation
            int signaled = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);
            if (signaled == 1)
                break; // cancellation requested

            _newEvent.Reset();

            string? item = null;
            lock (_lock)
            {
                if (_queue.Count > 0)
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
            }

            if (item is not null)
                Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();           // wakes WaitAny via token.WaitHandle
        _thread?.Join(5000);     // wait for graceful exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### What changed and why

| Original | Replacement | Reason |
|----------|-------------|--------|
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Loop must cooperatively check for cancellation |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles)` | Waits on **both** the event and `token.WaitHandle`, so cancellation unblocks instantly |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Token's `WaitHandle` becomes signaled, waking `WaitAny` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | *(removed)* | Cooperative cancellation means the loop exits on its own — no forced kill needed |
| — | `IDisposable` added | `CancellationTokenSource` and `ManualResetEvent` must be disposed to avoid timer/handle leaks |

### Pitfalls specific to this code

1. **Pre-existing race condition (preserved above, fix below):** If multiple `Enqueue` calls fire before the loop processes, `Set()`/`Reset()` can swallow signals and items pile up. The guard `if (_queue.Count > 0)` prevents the `Dequeue` crash, but items stall until the next `Set`.

2. **`CancellationToken` doesn't interrupt `Handle(item)`** — if `Handle` is long-running, cancellation waits until it returns. Pass the token into `Handle` and check it periodically inside.

3. **Don't forget to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — leaking it causes callback and timer leaks. Always wrap the owner in `IDisposable`.

### Bonus: Fully modernized version using `BlockingCollection<T>`

This eliminates the manual `ManualResetEvent` + lock + queue pattern and the race condition:

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly BlockingCollection<string> _queue = new();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        try
        {
            foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable(_cts.Token))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // expected on shutdown
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) => _queue.Add(item);

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();
        _thread?.Join(5000);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _queue.Dispose();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

`BlockingCollection<T>` handles all the synchronization internally, `GetConsumingEnumerable` blocks until an item arrives or the token is cancelled, and the `OperationCanceledException` catch replaces the old `ThreadAbortException` pattern. This is the recommended approach for .NET 8.
